12 ad uultum etiam dedrum: because fruits and victims were offered to the gods. Cato’s treatise has also many rules ior divine worship. When the master comes home, the first thing he does is larem familiarem salutare (c. 2); he is to be the priest in his own establishment, scito dominam pro tota familia rem divinam facere (c.143). The treatise also contains minute directions for the purification of the fields by a saoci- taurilia(c.141); for appeasing the country gods on disturbing a lucras (c. 139) ; for offerings to Silvanus in behalf of the oxen (c. 83), and other such matters.
